🔹 1. Parameters vs Arguments (you already saw this)

Parameters → in definition

Arguments → in call


🔹 3. Stack vs Heap

Stack → stores method calls & primitive variables

Heap → stores objects

int x = 10;          // stack
ListNode node = new ListNode(5);  // object in heap

👉 Confusion: variable node is on stack, object is in heap.

🔹 4. Primitive vs Reference Types
int a = 5;
int b = a;  // copy

b = 10;
// a is still 5
ListNode n1 = new ListNode(5);
ListNode n2 = n1;

n2.val = 10;
// n1.val is ALSO 10 😵

Primitives → copy value

Objects → copy reference

🔹 5. Pass by Value (but feels like reference 😅)

Java is always pass-by-value, but:

void change(ListNode node) {
    node.val = 100;
}

This does modify the object → confusing!

👉 Why? Because the reference is passed by value, not the object.



---------------------------------------------------------------------

int x = 10;
change(x);
System.out.println(x);

void change(int x) {
    x = 20;
}

✅ Correct — A) 10

✔️ Why?
Java is pass-by-value
A copy of x is passed to change()
Changing it inside the method does not affect the original

🔥 Question 3

What will be the output?

ListNode node = new ListNode(5);
change(node);
System.out.println(node.val);

void change(ListNode n) {
    n.val = 20;
}

✅ Correct — B) 20

✔️ Why?
The reference to the object is passed by value
But both node and n point to the same object in memory
So changing n.val changes the original object

The reference to the object is passed by value By value or reference ?

Nice catch — this is exactly where people get confused 😄

“By value or by reference?”

👉 Java is ALWAYS pass-by-value.

But here’s the subtle truth:

For primitives → value is copied

For objects → reference is copied (not the object)

So:

✔️ It is pass-by-value of the reference



ListNode node = new ListNode(5);
change(node);
System.out.println(node.val);

void change(ListNode n) {
    n = new ListNode(20);
}

✅ Correct Answer: A) 5

✔️ Why?
void change(ListNode n) {
    n = new ListNode(20);
}

A new object is created

But only the local copy n now points to it

Original node is unchanged

Visual:

Before:

node ──► [5]
n    ──► [5]

After:

node ──► [5]
n    ──► [20]   (new object)

👉 So node.val is still 5

🔥 Key Rule to Remember

Modify object → ✅ reflects outside
Reassign reference → ❌ does NOT reflect outside


🔥 Question 8 (tricky linked list / object reference)

What will be the output?

ListNode node1 = new ListNode(1);
ListNode node2 = new ListNode(2);
node1.next = node2;

ListNode node3 = node1;
node3.val = 10;

System.out.println(node1.val);

the correct answer is C) 10 ✅

✔️ Explanation
ListNode node1 = new ListNode(1);
ListNode node2 = new ListNode(2);
node1.next = node2;

ListNode node3 = node1;  // node3 references the SAME object as node1
node3.val = 10;

node3 points to the same object as node1

So changing node3.val also changes node1.val

System.out.println(node1.val); // 10

🔹 Key Idea
Assignment of objects → copies reference, not the object
Both variables point to same memory location


In Java, arrays of primitives are automatically initialized with default values:

int → 0
double → 0.0
boolean → false

Arrays of objects → default is null

int[] arr = new int[3];  // [0, 0, 0]
System.out.println(arr[0]); // 0

🔥 Question 11 (very tricky — String + compile-time)

String s1 = "ab" + "c";
String s2 = "abc";

System.out.println(s1 == s2);

correct answer is A) true ✅

✔️ Why?
String s1 = "ab" + "c";
String s2 = "abc";

"ab" + "c" is a compile-time constant expression

Java optimizes it at compile time → becomes "abc"

So both s1 and s2 point to the same string in the pool

🔥 Key Insight
Compile-time concatenation → goes to string pool
Runtime concatenation → creates new object

🔥 Question 12 (this is where people slip 😈)

What will be the output?

String s1 = "abc";
String s2 = "ab";
String s3 = s2 + "c";

System.out.println(s1 == s3);

correct answer is B) false ✅

✔️ Why?
String s1 = "abc";
String s2 = "ab";
String s3 = s2 + "c";

s1 → string literal → stored in string pool
s2 → also in string pool

BUT:
String s3 = s2 + "c";

👉 This happens at runtime, not compile time
👉 Java creates a new String object in heap

So:
s1 == s3  // false ❌ (different references)

But:
s1.equals(s3) // true ✅ (same content)

🔥 Key Rule
"a" + "b" → compile-time → pooled
variable + "b" → runtime → new object

🔥 Question 13 (reference trap 😈)

What will be the output?

int[] arr1 = {1, 2, 3};
int[] arr2 = arr1;

arr2[0] = 10;

System.out.println(arr1[0]);

correct answer is B) 10 ✅

✔️ Why?
int[] arr1 = {1, 2, 3};
int[] arr2 = arr1;

arr2 = arr1 does NOT create a new array
Both variables point to the same array in memory

Then:
arr2[0] = 10;

You modify the shared array

So:
System.out.println(arr1[0]); // 10

🔹 Visual
arr1 ──► [1, 2, 3]
arr2 ──► same array

After change:
arr1 ──► [10, 2, 3]
arr2 ──► same array

🔥 Key Rule
Arrays are objects in Java
Assignment copies reference, not data

🔥 Question 14 (method + array trap 😈)

What will be the output?

int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
change(arr);
System.out.println(arr[0]);

void change(int[] a) {
    a[0] = 99;
}
correct answer is B) 99 ✅

✔️ Why?
int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
change(arr);

Arrays are objects

The reference is passed by value, but still points to the same array

Inside method:
void change(int[] a) {
    a[0] = 99;
}

a and arr point to the same array

So modifying a[0] changes the original array

🔹 Key Reminder

Modify object/array → ✅ affects original

Reassign reference → ❌ does NOT affect original

🔥 Question 15 (FINAL boss 😈)

What will be the output?

int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
change(arr);
System.out.println(arr[0]);

void change(int[] a) {
    a = new int[]{9, 9, 9};
}

✅ Correct — A) 1 🎯

✔️ Why?
int[] arr = {1, 2, 3};
change(arr);

arr reference is passed (by value) to a

Inside method:
void change(int[] a) {
    a = new int[]{9, 9, 9};
}

👉 This is the key:

You are reassigning a to a new array

This does NOT affect the original arr

Visual:

Before:

arr ──► [1, 2, 3]
a   ──► same array

After reassignment:

arr ──► [1, 2, 3]
a   ──► [9, 9, 9]   (new array)
So:
System.out.println(arr[0]); //


🔥 BIG takeaway from all questions

👉 This is the rule that solves 90% of confusion:

Java is always pass-by-value

BUT:
Modifying object → affects original ✅
Reassigning reference → does NOT ❌